dual flourishing. By outlining how state-framed forms of love create desires that cannot be fulfilled, Zhang places China at the forefront of using affective attachments to nation, leader, and family in the global shifts toward exploitation and authoritarianism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aCommunism and lovezChina. 0aGlobalizationzChina. 0aMigration, InternalzChinaxHistory. 0aNationalismzChina. 0aNeoliberalismzChina. 0aRural-urban migrationzChina. 0aSex rolezChina. 0aWomenxEmploymentzChina. 0aWomenzChinaxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aWork and familyxGovernment policyzChina. 0aWork and familyzChina. 0aWork-life balancezChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022619423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022619/original  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles